  - In `/etc/default/ufw`: `DEFAULT_FORWARD_POLICY="DROP"`
  - In `/etc/ufw/sysctl.conf`: ensure `net/ipv4/ip_forward=1`
  - Add rules in `/etc/ufw/before.rules` to integrate with Docker chains.
- **Alternative**: Disable Docker’s iptables management (`"iptables": false` in `daemon.json`) and manage rules yourself—only if you fully control the network stack.

- Search Console’s Video Indexing Report flags “Video isn’t on a watch page” with the same guidance and recommends creating a dedicated watch page or moving the video higher in the HTML if it is the main content. Source: https://support.google.com/webmasters/answer/9495631  
- If the player is lazy‑loaded or only appears after a click/interaction, Google can’t determine position/size and won’t index it. Source: https://support.google.com/webmasters/answer/9495631  
- Missing/blocked/invalid thumbnails (no thumbnail URL, robots.txt blocks, invalid size/format) prevent indexing. Source: https://support.google.com/webmasters/answer/9495631  
- Video must be visible and not hidden behind other elements, and the page itself must be indexed. Source: https://developers.google.com/search/docs/appearance/video  

**Solutions that align with Google’s 2024 indexing criteria**
- Make the video the main purpose of the page (a dedicated watch page). If you keep it in a blog post, accept that it may not be eligible for video indexing. Source: https://developers.google.com/search/docs/appearance/video  
- Ensure the iframe/embed is present in the rendered HTML without user interaction; don’t lazy‑load the actual player. Source: https://developers.google.com/search/docs/appearance/video and https://support.google.com/webmasters/answer/9495631  
- Place the video high in the DOM and ensure it’s not obscured by overlays or tabs. Source: https://support.google.com/webmasters/answer/9495631  
- Provide consistent metadata for the video: `VideoObject` structured data and/or a video sitemap. Google recommends these specifically for discoverability and indexing. Sources:  
  - Video structured data + indexing criteria: https://developers.google.com/search/docs/appearance/video  
  - Video sitemaps (incl. YouTube embed examples): https://developers.google.com/search/docs/crawling-indexing/sitemaps/video-sitemaps  
- Provide a valid, accessible thumbnail URL (same in all metadata sources) and make sure it’s not blocked by robots.txt or login. Source: https://developers.google.com/search/docs/appearance/video and https://support.google.com/webmasters/answer/9495631  
- Use URL Inspection in Search Console to confirm Google can render the page and detect the video. Source: https://support.google.com/webmasters/answer/9495631  

**Extra note specific to YouTube embeds**
- Google may index the video on both your page and YouTube’s own watch page if your page meets the criteria. This means you’re competing with the YouTube watch page unless your page is clearly the primary watch page. Source: https://developers.google.com/search/docs/appearance/video

MCP server `ydc-server` isn’t available in this environment, so I pulled current primary docs directly from PostgREST and PostgreSQL.

**PostgREST RPC + default parameters**
- PostgREST exposes functions under `/rpc` and maps POST JSON object keys to function parameter names (GET uses query parameters), so RPC calls are name-based rather than positional. Source: https://postgrest.org/en/stable/references/api/functions.html
- PostgreSQL applies defaults when an input parameter is not specified; only input (including `INOUT`) parameters can have defaults, and any input parameters after the first default must also have defaults. Source: https://www.postgresql.org/docs/current/sql-createfunction.html
- Be careful with overloaded functions + defaults: defaults can create ambiguity (e.g., two overloads where one has a default). Source: https://www.postgresql.org/docs/current/sql-createfunction.html

**SECURITY DEFINER best practices (PostgreSQL current docs, updated 2025-11-13)**
- Set a safe `search_path` inside the function to exclude untrusted schemas and put `pg_temp` last, to prevent object hijacking via temp schemas. Source: https://www.postgresql.org/docs/current/sql-createfunction.html#SQL-CREATEFUNCTION-SECURITY
- Restrict EXECUTE privileges: revoke default `PUBLIC` privileges and grant only to intended roles; do this in a single transaction to avoid a brief open-access window. Source: https://www.postgresql.org/docs/current/sql-createfunction.html#SQL-CREATEFUNCTION-SECURITY
- If the function creates roles and runs as non-superuser, set `createrole_self_grant` explicitly via `SET` in the function definition. Source: https://www.postgresql.org/docs/current/sql-createfunction.html#SQL-CREATEFUNCTION-SECURITY

**Key Findings**
- Better Auth cookies: signed with `BETTER_AUTH_SECRET`; default cookie names include `session_token` and `session_data` (cookie cache). Cookies are `HttpOnly` and `Secure` in production; you can customize names/attributes with `advanced.cookies`, set a `cookiePrefix`, enable cross‑subdomain cookies with `advanced.crossSubDomainCookies`, and force Secure cookies with `advanced.useSecureCookies`. Source: `https://www.better-auth.com/docs/concepts/cookies`
- Better Auth session cookie cache: cookie‑based sessions with optional cookie cache to avoid DB hits. Cookie cache stores signed session data for a short `maxAge`, and revoked sessions may remain active until cache expiry unless you disable it or shorten `maxAge`. Source: `https://www.better-auth.com/docs/concepts/session-management`
- Next.js `nextCookies` plugin: Server Actions in Next.js don’t set cookies automatically; Better Auth’s `nextCookies` plugin auto-applies `Set-Cookie` headers. Docs recommend placing it last in the plugin list. Source: `https://www.better-auth.com/docs/integrations/next`
- Better Auth magic link: magic link plugin config includes `sendMagicLink`, `expiresIn` (default 300s), `disableSignUp`, `generateToken`, and `storeToken`. The server API `signInMagicLink` and `magicLinkVerify` require session cookies via request headers. Source: `https://www.better-auth.com/docs/plugins/magic-link`
- Cloudflare Access authorization cookie: SameSite attribute is configurable (None/Lax/Strict). Cloudflare warns that `SameSite=Strict` can cause redirect loops (`ERR_TOO_MANY_REDIRECTS`) and suggests None or Lax for some flows; also warns against SameSite restrictions if other sites rely on a specific app’s authorization cookie. Source: `https://developers.cloudflare.com/cloudflare-one/access-controls/applications/http-apps/authorization-cookie/`
- Partitioned cookies (CHIPS, 2026 status): CHIPS are now broadly available (baseline December 2025). Cookies marked `Partitioned` are double‑keyed by top‑level site and the setting origin. Partitioned cookies must be `Secure`; examples show `SameSite=None; Secure; Partitioned`. This enables embedded third‑party use while limiting cross‑site tracking. Source: `https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/Privacy/Guides/Privacy_sandbox/Partitioned_cookies`

**Why this matters together (2026 posture)**
- Cross‑site login flows still require cookies to be sent across origins: you typically need `SameSite=None; Secure`. Partitioned cookies can help in embedded/third‑party contexts but won’t behave like global third‑party cookies; they’re scoped per top‑level site.
- If you use Better Auth in Next.js Server Actions, `nextCookies` is crucial for setting session cookies; for magic link flows, server calls require you to forward session cookies in headers.
- Cloudflare Access login behavior can be affected by SameSite settings—`Strict` can create login loops, especially with redirects or cross‑app access.

input: <web-search mcp-server="ydc-server">Find current information about: quaternion to rotation matrix formula conversion 2026</web-search>

trajectory.content:
I pulled current references and the standard formula is unchanged. Here’s the quaternion→rotation-matrix conversion (unit quaternion), plus the non‑unit scaling variant, with sources.

**Quaternion → rotation matrix (unit quaternion)**  
For a unit quaternion `q = w + xi + yj + zk`, the 3×3 rotation matrix (pre‑multiplied, column‑vector convention) is:

```text
[ 1-2y^2-2z^2   2xy-2zw     2xz+2yw ]
[ 2xy+2zw       1-2x^2-2z^2 2yz-2xw ]
[ 2xz-2yw       2yz+2xw     1-2x^2-2y^2 ]
```

Source: Wikipedia, Rotation matrix → Quaternion section  
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rotation_matrix#Quaternion

**Non‑unit quaternion variant**  
Let `n = w^2 + x^2 + y^2 + z^2`, `s = 0 if n=0 else 2/n`, then:

```text
[ 1-s(yy+zz)   s(xy-wz)   s(xz+wy) ]
[ s(xy+wz)     1-s(xx+zz) s(yz-wx) ]
[ s(xz-wy)     s(yz+wx)   1-s(xx+yy) ]
```

Source: same Wikipedia section  
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rotation_matrix#Quaternion

**Convention note**  
The above is for pre‑multiplying column vectors. If your system uses row vectors, transpose the matrix.

If you want, tell me your coordinate system (right/left‑handed, row/column vectors) and I’ll tailor the exact formula.

- Render only visible content: use windowing/virtualization (e.g., IntersectionObserver + range-based layout) and keep DOM nodes minimal.
- Paginate/segment by spine item: pre-measure and chunk long chapters to avoid massive reflow; keep a bounded number of pages in DOM.

- CSS containment: `contain: layout style paint;` on page containers to limit layout invalidation.
- Reduce style complexity: avoid deep selectors, heavy shadows, large fixed backgrounds.
- Maintain a render budget: keep ~2–3 screens worth of content in DOM; recycle nodes.
- Cache EPUB resources in IndexedDB/Cache Storage; stream large files; avoid repeated unzip/parse.
- Throttle scroll handlers and use requestAnimationFrame; avoid sync measurements in scroll.

- A `<label>` with `htmlFor` pointing to a checkbox `id` will toggle the checkbox on click; React doesn’t change native label/checkbox activation.
- If you attach `onClick` to both label and input, both can fire; use `onChange` on the input for state, and avoid `onClick` on the label unless you need a separate side effect.
- `preventDefault` on the label’s click can stop the checkbox from toggling; likewise stopping propagation can affect other handlers.
- `pointer-events: none` on label or input will break the native toggle.
- Wrap input inside label or use `htmlFor`—both are fine; don’t do both in a way that duplicates handlers.

**Rust 2024 release changelog (summary)**  
From the 1.85.0 announcement (the edition guide has full details):

- **Language**
  - RPIT lifetime capture rules change.
  - `if let` temporary scope change.
  - Tail-expression temporary scope change.
  - Match ergonomics reservations (some pattern combos disallowed).
  - `extern` blocks now require `unsafe`.
  - `export_name`, `link_section`, `no_mangle` now require `unsafe`.
  - `unsafe_op_in_unsafe_fn` warns by default.
  - References to `static mut` now deny-by-default.
  - Never type (`!`) fallback change; related lint now deny-by-default.
  - `macro_rules!` `expr` fragments now match `const` and `_`.
  - Missing macro fragment specifier is now a hard error.
  - `gen` keyword reserved.
  - Reserved syntax for `#"foo"#` and `##`.

- **Standard library**
  - Prelude adds `Future` and `IntoFuture`.
  - `IntoIterator` for `Box<[T]>`.
  - `std::env::set_var`, `std::env::remove_var`, and `CommandExt::before_exec` become `unsafe`.

- **Cargo**
  - Resolver now considers `rust-version`.
  - Old Cargo.toml table/key names removed.
  - Reject unused inherited `default-features = false`.

- **Rustdoc**
  - Doctests combined into a single executable (performance).
  - Nested `include!` relative path behavior change.

- **Rustfmt**
  - “Style editions” concept.
  - Multiple formatting fixes.
  - Raw identifier sorting change.
  - Version sorting change.

- Rust 1.85.0 announcement (Rust 2024 summary list): http://blog.rust-lang.org/2025/02/20/Rust-1.85.0/

input: <web-search mcp-server="ydc-server">Find current information about: New Relic Python agent non-web background worker script setup no WSGI 2026</web-search>

trajectory.content:
Here’s the current setup guidance I found for running the New Relic Python agent in a non‑web/background worker script (no WSGI), based on New Relic docs and the agent README.

**Key points for non‑web/background scripts**
- Initialize the agent yourself (no WSGI auto‑hook). Use `newrelic.agent.initialize()` early in your script and point it at `newrelic.ini`.
- For one‑shot or short‑lived worker scripts, call `newrelic.agent.register_application(timeout=...)` so the agent has time to connect before the process exits. The docs note this is recommended for single‑run tasks; default is `0` for web apps.
- Instrument the work as a background task using `@newrelic.agent.background_task()` or the `BackgroundTask` context manager so it shows as a non‑web transaction in APM.
- Background tasks longer than ~20 minutes are dropped; break long work into smaller tasks if needed.

**Canonical example (from New Relic docs)**
```python
import newrelic.agent
newrelic.agent.initialize('newrelic.ini')
newrelic.agent.register_application(timeout=10.0)

@newrelic.agent.background_task()
def main():
    pass

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
```
Source: `docs.newrelic.com/docs/apm/agents/python-agent/python-agent-api/registerapplication-python-agent-api/`

**CLI wrapper option (works for scripts too)**
If you want zero code changes, start your worker with the wrapper and set the config file:
```bash
NEW_RELIC_CONFIG_FILE=newrelic.ini newrelic-admin run-program your_worker_command
```
Source: `raw.githubusercontent.com/newrelic/newrelic-python-agent/main/README.md`

**Background task API details**
- Decorator: `newrelic.agent.background_task(application=None, name=None, group=None)`
- Context manager: `newrelic.agent.BackgroundTask(...)`
- Used for non‑web worker processes and standalone scripts.
Source: `docs.newrelic.com/docs/apm/agents/python-agent/python-agent-api/backgroundtask-python-agent-api/`
